To convert Markdown formatted text into HTML using C++, you can use a library like `markdowncpp`. Below is an example of how you could implement such a function:

1. First, ensure you have the `markdowncpp` library installed in your project. If not, you can include it through a package manager or install it from GitHub.

2. Here's a basic implementation assuming you've included the necessary headers:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <sstream>

// Function to convert Markdown to HTML
std::string markdown_to_html(const std::string& markdown) {
    // Create a stream for input
    std::istringstream iss(markdown);

    // Read the input as markdown
    std::string line;
    while (getline(iss, line)) {
        // Use markdowncpp to process each line
        std::stringstream ss(line);
        std::string token;
        std::ostringstream oss;

        while (std::getline(ss, token, '#')) {
            if (!token.empty()) {  // Ensure we don't add empty lines
                oss << "<h" << token.size() << ">" << token << "</h" << token.size() << ">\n";
            }
        }

        // Add any remaining content after processing headings
        oss << std::endl << std::endl;

        // Append the processed section to the final string
        oss << line.substr(token.size());
    }

    return oss.str();
}

int main() {
    std::string markdown = "# Heading\n## Subheading\n### Nested\n* Item one\n* Item two";

    std::cout << "Markdown:\n" << markdown << "\n\nHTML:\n" << markdown_to_html(markdown) << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

This code defines a function `markdown_to_html` which takes a string containing Markdown-formatted text as its parameter. It processes this text according to the rules defined by the Markdown language, generating corresponding HTML output. The resulting HTML is returned as a string.

